# Engineering Operating Model (EOM)

## Repository Strategy & Framework Design Summary

---

# Vision

The **Engineering Operating Model (EOM)** is a framework for building enterprise software through a governed, specification-driven, domain-centric engineering methodology.

It is **not** an AI framework.

It is **not** a prompt library.

It is an **Engineering Operating System** that defines how engineering is performed while allowing humans and AI to collaborate using the same standards, workflows, and governance.

AI is an acceleratorвЂ”not the foundation.

---

# Design Philosophy

The framework is built on the following principles:

* Product Agnostic
* Technology Agnostic
* AI Agnostic
* Specification Driven
* Domain Driven
* Test Driven
* Documentation First
* Governance Driven
* Continuously Evolvable

Every engineering activity should produce measurable engineering artifacts.

Documentation is treated as code.

---

# Repository Philosophy

The repository itself should be treated as an open-source engineering product.

This means:

* Versioned releases
* Roadmaps
* Milestones
* Sprints
* ADRs
* Standards
* Reviews
* Continuous improvement

The framework should evolve exactly as the software built with it evolves.

---

# Documentation Philosophy

Every Markdown document should be production quality.

Documents should not be notes.

They should be publishable engineering documentation.

Every document should contain, where applicable:

* Metadata
* Purpose
* Scope
* Audience
* Responsibilities
* Inputs
* Outputs
* Dependencies
* Relationships
* Mermaid diagrams
* Examples
* References
* Future evolution
* Version history

Every document should be independently understandable.

A reader landing on any page should understand:

* Why the document exists
* Where it fits
* What depends on it
* What it depends on

---

# Documentation Metadata Standard

Every document begins with a metadata block.

```yaml
---
title:
version:
status:
owner:
author:
last_updated:
---
```

This makes the repository feel like an enterprise engineering handbook rather than a collection of Markdown files.

